<exercises xml:id="exercises-proof-methods">

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-prime-def-1"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::prime.def.1} -->
	Let <m>n</m> represent an integer with <m>n \ge 2</m>.
	Prove that <m>n</m> is prime if and only if <m>n/m</m> is <em>not</em> an integer for every integer <m>m</m> with <m>2 \le m \lt \frac{n}{2}</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-prime-def-2"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::prime.def.2} -->
	Let <m>n</m> represent an integer with <m>n \ge 2</m>.
	Suppose <m>p_1,p_2,\dotsc,p_\ell</m> is a complete list of prime numbers which are less than or equal to <m>n/2</m>.
	Prove that <m>n</m> is prime if and only if none of the <m>p_i</m> divide <m>n</m>.
	<alert>Careful:</alert>
	Is the statement actually true in the case <m>n=2</m>? <m>n=3</m>?
	(Why should these cases be given special consideration?)
</p></exercise>

<exercise>
	<introduction><p>
		Call two people <term>twins</term> if they share the same mother and the same birthdate.
		Consider the statement: <q>if two people are twins, then they share the same birthdate.</q>
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> Is the statement true? </p></task>
	<task><p> What is the converse of this statement? Is it true? </p></task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-direct-1"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::direct.proof.1} -->
	<em>Prove directly:</em> The sum of two rational numbers is a rational number.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-direct-2"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::direct.proof.2} -->
	<em>Prove directly:</em> If <m>n</m> is even, then <m>n^2</m> is divisible by <m>4</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-direct-3">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::direct.proof.3} -->
	<p> Recall that the <term>triangle inequality</term> states that <m>\abs{x+y} \le \abs{x} + \abs{y}</m> for all numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>. </p>
	<p><em>Use the triangle inequality to prove directly:</em> <m>\abs{x+y+z} \le \abs{x} + \abs{y} + \abs{z}</m> for all numbers <m>x,y,z</m>. </p>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-cases">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::cases.proof} -->
	<statement><p><em>Prove by reduction to cases:</em> <m>n^3 - n</m> is always divisible by <m>3</m>. </p></statement>
	<hint><p>Use cases <m>n = 3m, 3m+1, 3m+2</m>.</p></hint>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-contrapos">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::contrapos.proof} -->
	<statement><p><em>Prove by proving the contrapositive:</em> if <m>2^n - 1</m> is prime, then <m>n</m> is prime. </p></statement>
	<hint><p>
		You may find the following <q>difference of powers</q> factorization formula useful:
		<me> x^m - y^m = (x-y)(x^{m-1} + x^{m-2}y + x^{m-3}y^2 + \dotsb + x^2y^{m-3} + x y^{m-2} + y^{m-1}). </me>
	</p></hint>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-counterexample">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::counterexample.proof} -->
	<p>Prove by counterexample that the following statement is false.</p>
	<blockquote><p> The sum of any two irrational numbers is irrational. </p></blockquote>
	<p>(See <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-direct-1" />.)</p>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methds-bicond">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::bicond.proof} -->
	<p><em>Prove the biconditional:</em> <m>n</m> is even if and only if <m>n^2</m> is divisible by <m>4</m>.</p>
	<p>(See <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-direct-2" />.)</p>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-contradiction-1"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::contradiction.proof.1} -->
	<em>Prove by contradiction:</em>
	If <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are integers such that <m>11m + 19n</m> is odd, then either <m>m</m> or <m>n</m> (or both) must be odd.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-contradiction-2"><p>
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::contradiction.proof.2} -->
	<em>Prove by contradiction:</em> For <m>x,y>0</m>, <m>\sqrt{x+y} \ne \sqrt{x} + \sqrt{y}</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-contradiction-3">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::contradiction.proof.3} -->
	<p><em>Prove by contradiction:</em> The sum of a rational number and an irrational number is irrational.</p>
	<p>(See <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-direct-1" /> and <xref ref="exercise-proof-methods-counterexample" />.)</p>
</exercise>

<exercise><p>
	Prove that if <m>\ell</m>, <m>m</m>, and <m>n</m> are integers such that <m>\ell</m> divides <m>m</m> and <m>\ell</m> divides <m>n</m>, then <m>\ell</m> divides <m>mn</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise><p>
	Prove that if <m>\ell</m>, <m>m</m>, and <m>n</m> are integers such that <m>mn</m> divides <m>\ell</m>, then both <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> divide <m>\ell</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercise><p>
	Suppose that <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are integers, and <m>p</m> is a prime number.
	Prove that if <m>p</m> does not divide the product <m>mn</m>, then <m>p</m> cannot divide either of <m>m</m> or <m>n</m>.
</p></exercise>

<exercisegroup xml:id="exercisegroup-proof-methods-square-number-square-free">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::proof.methods::square.number.square.free} -->
	<title>Working with a definition</title>
	<introduction>
		<p> <xref ref="exercisegroup-proof-methods-square-number-square-free" text="type-local">Exercises</xref> concern the following definitions. </p>
		<p>
		A <term>square number</term><idx><h>square</h><h>number</h></idx>
		is an integer which is equal to the square of some integer.
		An integer is <term>square free</term><idx><h>square</h><h>free</h></idx>
		if it is not divisible by any square number other than <m>1</m>.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-square-number-square-free-1">
		<introduction><p> For each of the following, provide a proof to justify your answer. </p></introduction>
		<task><p> Is <m>0</m> a square number? Is it square free? </p></task>
		<task><p> Does there exist a negative square number? </p></task>
		<task><p> Is every negative number square free? </p></task>
		<task><p> Is every prime number square free? </p></task>
		<task><p> Is every square free number prime? </p></task>
		<task><p> Does there exist an integer which is both a square number and square free? </p></task>
	</exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-square-number-square-free-2"><p>
		Prove that a positive number <m>n</m> is square free if and only if for every factorization <m>n = ab</m>,
		the integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> do not share a common factor other than <m>1</m>.
	</p></exercise>
	<exercise xml:id="exercise-proof-methods-square-number-square-free-3"><p>
		Prove that a positive number is square free if and only if it is not divisible by the square of a prime number.
	</p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<!-- TODO add link to a table of small primes ? -->
<exercise>
	<introduction><p>
		A pair of prime numbers <m>p_1,p_2</m> is called a <term>twin prime pair</term> if <m>p_2 = p_1 + 2</m>.
		A prime number is called an <term>isolated prime</term><idx><h>isolated</h><h>prime</h></idx>
		if it is not part of a twin prime pair.
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> Determine the first (<ie /> smallest) four twin prime pairs. </p></task>
	<task><p> Determine the first (<ie /> smallest) two isolated primes. </p></task>
	<task><p> Prove that if <m>p, p+2</m> is a twin prime pair with <m>p \ge 5</m>, then <m>p+1</m> is divisible by <m>6</m>. </p></task>
	<task><p> Prove that if <m>p, p+2</m> is a twin prime pair, then <m>p-2,p</m> and <m>p+2,p+4</m> <em>cannot</em> be twin prime pairs. </p></task>
</exercise>

</exercises>
